This should be added to the FAQ on www.junit.org.

--- dror2@... wrote:
&gt; Thus we can summarise the pattern for Exception testing:
&gt; 
&gt; try {
&gt;         //tested code starts here.
&gt;         ...
&gt; 
&gt; fail( &quot;should have thrown exception TestedException&quot; )
&gt; } catch ( TestedException ) { return }
&gt; } catch ( Exception e ) { fail( &quot;thrown wrong exception: &quot;+e ); }
&gt; 
&gt; 
&gt; I have written an extension to TestCase, that gives the above
&gt; behaviour.
&gt; Instead of the try/catch blocks, you call a single method at the
&gt; beginning 
&gt; of the test
&gt;         shouldThrow( TestedException.class );
&gt; and the TestCase does the rest.
&gt; 
&gt; Anyone, let me know if it is of any interest.
&gt; 
&gt; (the reason I&#39;m not sure its useful, is what Kent has written about
&gt; the 
&gt; simplicity of the framework: I&#39;m not sure the complexity of adding
&gt; an 
&gt; extra method to TestCase justify the removal of the above 4-line
&gt; patten)
&gt; 
&gt; 
&gt; 
&gt; 
&gt; 
&gt; &quot;Jason Rogers&quot; &lt;jason.rogers@...&gt;
&gt; 14/07/2001 22:17
&gt; Please respond to junit
&gt; 
&gt;  
&gt;         To:     &quot;&#39;junit@yahoogroups.com&#39;&quot; &lt;junit@yahoogroups.com&gt;
&gt;         cc: 
&gt;         Subject:        RE: [junit] How do I implement a test case
&gt; for a thrown exception ?
&gt; 
&gt; 
&gt; No.  The fail() immediately following isPartnerAssigned() would
&gt; fail the
&gt; test if the exception was not thrown.  If any other exception is
&gt; thrown, 
&gt; the
&gt; catch{} for those would fail the test.  You could add another catch
&gt; for
&gt; java.lang.Exception in case you think that might be thrown, but it
&gt; doesn&#39;t
&gt; sound like the contract for your method.
&gt; 
&gt; -Jason
&gt; 
&gt;     &gt; You still need a fail after the try/catch to account for the
&gt;     &gt; possibility that no exception was thrown.
&gt;     &gt;
&gt;     &gt; --- Jason Rogers &lt;jason.rogers@...&gt; wrote:
&gt;     &gt; &gt; If you want to eliminate the boolean, use your first
&gt;     &gt; example and do
&gt;     &gt; &gt; the
&gt;     &gt; &gt; assert in the catch block.
&gt;     &gt; &gt;
&gt;     &gt; &gt;     public void test_00_isPartnerAssigned() {
&gt;     &gt; &gt;
&gt;     &gt; &gt;         try {
&gt;     &gt; &gt;
&gt;     &gt; instancePartnerHierarchyWorker.isPartnerAssigned(null);
&gt;     &gt; &gt;             fail(&quot;IllegalArgumentException should be
&gt; thrown.&quot;);
&gt;     &gt; &gt;
&gt;     &gt; &gt;         } catch (IllegalArgumentException iae) {
&gt;     &gt; &gt;
&gt;     &gt; &gt;             assert(true);
&gt;     &gt; &gt;
&gt;     &gt; &gt;         } catch (PartnerNotFoundException pnfe){
&gt;     &gt; &gt;
&gt;     &gt; &gt;             fail(&quot;PartnerNotFoundException should not
&gt;     &gt; be thrown.&quot;);
&gt;     &gt; &gt;
&gt;     &gt; &gt;         } catch (PersistenceException pe){
&gt;     &gt; &gt;
&gt;     &gt; &gt;             fail(&quot;PersistenceException should not be
&gt; thrown.&quot;);
&gt;     &gt; &gt;         }
&gt;     &gt; &gt;     }
&gt;     &gt; &gt;
&gt;     &gt; &gt;     &gt; -----Original Message-----
&gt;     &gt; &gt;     &gt; From: Mike Duffy [mailto:mduffy_lists@...]
&gt;     &gt; &gt;     &gt; Sent: Friday, July 13, 2001 11:24 PM
&gt;     &gt; &gt;     &gt; To: junit@yahoogroups.com
&gt;     &gt; &gt;     &gt; Subject: Re: [junit] How do I implement a test case
&gt; for a
&gt;     &gt; &gt; thrown
&gt;     &gt; &gt;     &gt; exception?
&gt;     &gt; &gt;     &gt;
&gt;     &gt; &gt;     &gt;
&gt;     &gt; &gt;     &gt; Also, this is better than the structure I originally
&gt;     &gt; &gt;     &gt; proposed because
&gt;     &gt; &gt;     &gt; it eliminates the need for a boolean flag.
&gt;     &gt; &gt;     &gt;
&gt;     &gt; &gt;     &gt; --- Vladimir Bossicard &lt;vladimir@...&gt;
&gt; wrote:
&gt;     &gt; &gt;     &gt; &gt; &gt; The Junit.org site has an FAQ section
&gt;     &gt; &gt;     &gt; &gt; &gt; (http://junit.sourceforge.net/doc/faq/faq.htm)
&gt; with
&gt;     &gt; &gt;     &gt; the following
&gt;     &gt; &gt;     &gt; &gt; &gt; question: How do I implement a test case for a
&gt; thrown
&gt;     &gt; &gt;     &gt; exception?
&gt;     &gt; &gt;     &gt; &gt; &gt;
&gt;     &gt; &gt;     &gt; &gt; &gt; The answer they give is not completely
&gt;     &gt; correct because it
&gt;     &gt; &gt; does
&gt;     &gt; &gt;     &gt; &gt; not
&gt;     &gt; &gt;     &gt; &gt; &gt; account for the possiblility that another
&gt;     &gt; exception could
&gt;     &gt; &gt; be
&gt;     &gt; &gt;     &gt; &gt; thrown.
&gt;     &gt; &gt;     &gt; &gt;
&gt;     &gt; &gt;     &gt; &gt; I think they assume that your method only throws
&gt; one
&gt;     &gt; &gt;     &gt; exception.  If
&gt;     &gt; &gt;     &gt; &gt; your method throws more exceptions, you can use:
&gt;     &gt; &gt;     &gt; &gt;
&gt;     &gt; &gt;     &gt; &gt; // Test IllegalArgumentException is thrown when
&gt;     &gt; &gt;     &gt; partnerID is null.
&gt;     &gt; &gt;     &gt; &gt; public void test_00_isPartnerAssigned() {
&gt;     &gt; &gt;     &gt; &gt;    try {
&gt;     &gt; &gt;     &gt; &gt;       boolean assignedStatus =
&gt;     &gt; &gt;     &gt; &gt;
&gt;     &gt; &gt; instancePartnerHierarchyWorker.isPartnerAssigned(null);
&gt;     &gt; &gt;     &gt; &gt;    } catch (IllegalArgumentException e) {
&gt;     &gt; &gt;     &gt; &gt;       return;
&gt;     &gt; &gt;     &gt; &gt;    } catch (Exception e) {
&gt;     &gt; &gt;     &gt; &gt;       fail(&quot;IllegalArgumentException should have
&gt; been
&gt;     &gt; &gt; thrown.&quot;);
&gt;     &gt; &gt;     &gt; &gt;    }
&gt;     &gt; &gt;     &gt; &gt;    fail(&quot;IllegalArgumentException should have been
&gt;     &gt; &gt; thrown.&quot;);
&gt;     &gt; &gt;     &gt; &gt; }
&gt;     &gt; &gt;     &gt; &gt;
&gt;     &gt; &gt;     &gt; &gt; -Vladimir
